Generate Parameters

  1. Windspeeds (v):
  • normally distributed
  • mean of 300 cm/s
  • standard deviation of 50 cm/s
  1. Vegetation height (height):
  • between 3.5 and 5.5 m (but any value in that range is equally likely)
  1. k_d and k_0 parameters:
  • normally distributed
  • standard deviation of 1% of their default values

Sobol Analysis

  1. Use the Sobol approach to generate parameter values for the 4 parameters
source(here("Catm.R"))

# generate two examples of random number from parameter distributions

# number of samples
np <- 1000

# example 1
k_o <- rnorm(mean = 0.1, sd = 0.1 * 0.01, n = np)
k_d <- rnorm(mean = 0.7, sd = 0.7 * 0.01, n = np)
# in meters/s
v <- rnorm(mean = 3, sd = 0.5, n = np)
height <- runif(min = 3.5, max = 5.5, n = np)

X1 <- cbind.data.frame(k_o, k_d, v, height = height)

#example 2
# repeat sampling
k_o <- rnorm(mean = 0.1, sd = 0.1 * 0.01, n = np)
k_d <- rnorm(mean = 0.7, sd = 0.7 * 0.01, n = np)
# in meters/s
v <- rnorm(mean = 3, sd = 0.5, n = np)
height <- runif(min = 3.5, max = 5.5, n = np)

X2 <- cbind.data.frame(k_o, k_d, v, height = height)

# Use a Sobol approach implemented by jansen
sens_Catm_Sobol <- sobolSalt(model = NULL, X1, X2, nboot = 100)

#str(sens_Catm_Sobol)

# Take a look at the Sobol generated sensitivity object
# your parameters sets for sensitivity analysis are in X
#sens_Catm_Sobol$X
  1. Run the atmospheric conductance model for these parameters
# Turn results into df
parms <- as.data.frame(sens_Catm_Sobol$X) 

# Name the parameters 
colnames(parms) <- colnames(X1)

# Run model for all parameter sets
res <- pmap_dbl(parms, Catm) 

# Check
length(res) == nrow(parms)
[1] TRUE
# Supply model outputs
sens_Catm_Sobol <- sensitivity::tell(sens_Catm_Sobol, res, res.names = "ga")
  1. Plot conductance estimates in a way that accounts for parameter uncertainty
# Graph two most sensitive parameters
both <- cbind.data.frame(parms, gs = sens_Catm_Sobol$y) #gs is atmostpheric conductance (results)

# look at overall gs sensitvity to uncertainty
ggplot(both, aes(x = gs)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(both$gs), col = "cyan")

  1. Comment on what this tells you about how atmospheric conductance and its sensitivity to variation in windspeed differs in this setting as compared to the setting that we examined in class where windspeed was lower and less variable and vegetation was taller.

Atmospheric conductance is more sensitive to windspeed in this setting (with higher, more variable windespeed and shorter vegetation) vs.Â the setting we examined in class (with lower, less variable windspeed and taller vegetation). We know this by comparing the Sobol indices, where the indices for v and height are higher in this setting than the class setting, where k_d was the most sensitive (highest indice) parameter. This shed light on the role of windspeed and vegetation on atmospheric conductance, specifically concerning water vapor flux, in different environments.
